Claims CLAIMS  I claim: 1. A ladder cage, comprising: a plurality of ring members, the ring members having a first ring securing end and a second ring securing end; the ring members each having a plurality of self-contained latching members spaced along the length of the respective ring members; the self-contained latching members each having an anchoring end and a retaining end distal the anchoring end; and at least one of the self-contained latching members having a retaining member proximate the retaining end. 2. The ladder cage of claim 1, further comprising: the retaining member having a retaining end; wherein the self-contained latching members each have a latching member aperture extending through a portion of the side wall of the self-contained latching member, wherein the retaining member is positioned within the aperture; and the retaining member being movable between a compressed position and a non-compressed position, wherein in the non-compressed position the retaining end of the retaining member extends further outward from the aperture than when the retaining member is in its compressed position. 3. The ladder cage of claim 1, wherein the retaining member is positioned on the retaining end of at least one of the self-contained latching members. 4. The ladder cage of claim 2, further comprising a plurality of anchor plates spaced along the length of the respective ring members, wherein the anchor plates couple the corresponding self-contained latching members to the ring members. 5. The ladder cage of claim 4, further comprising: the self-contained latching member having a cavity extending at least partially therein; 

 the cavity ending at an innermost inner wall within the self-contained latching member; the latching member aperture extending along a portion of the sidewall proximate the cavity such that the cavity creates a passageway from the exterior of the self-contained latching member to the interior of the cavity; and wherein a portion of the retaining member is retained inside the cavity and a portion of the retaining member extends outside of the cavity through the aperture. 6. The ladder cage of claim 5, further comprising: a resilient member contained within the cavity of the self-contained latching member; the resilient member being compressible to allow for compression thereof when pressure is applied to the retainment end of the retainment member, and capable of returning to its original form, or close thereto, when it is no longer in a compressed state; the retaining member having an underside; and wherein a portion of the resilient member is in contact with the underside of the retaining member. 7. The ladder cage of claim 6, further comprising: each anchor plate having at least one ring attachment member extending therefrom and an aperture extending through a portion of the anchor plate; wherein the at least one ring attachment member attaches the anchor plate to the ring member; the self-contained latching member having external threading along a portion of its anchoring end; and wherein the anchoring end is placed within the anchor plate aperture and an internally threaded fastener is coupled to the external threading of the anchoring end to retain the self- contained latching member in the anchor plate aperture. 8. The ladder cage of claim 7, further comprising: an internal protrusion extending into the latching member cavity opposite the latching member aperture; the resilient member having a base and opposing arms extending from the base; 

 the resilient member base being proximate the innermost inner wall of the cavity; the bottom arm of the resilient member positioned proximate a portion of the internal protrusion; the upper arm of the resilient member being in contact with the underside of the resilient member; a striking plate having at one end the retainment member and at the opposite end a striking end; the self-contained latching member having a cavity opening extending through its retaining end; and wherein the striking end at least partially extends out of the cavity at the cavity opening. 9. The ladder cage of claim 7, further comprising: a latch member attachment coupled to each of the ring member's first ring securing end and second ring securing end; and a latching member body positioned along a portion of the external threading of the self- contained latching member's anchoring end, intermediate the anchor plate and the latching member aperture. 10. A ladder cage, comprising: a plurality of ring members, the ring members having a first ring securing end and a second ring securing end; the ring members each having a plurality of latching members spaced along the length of the respective ring members; the latching members each having an anchoring end and a retaining end distal the anchoring end; and at least one of the latching members having a retaining member disposed along a side of the latching member, wherein a portion of the length of the retaining member extends outward away from the outer surface of the latching member. 11. The ladder cage of claim 10, further comprising: 

 the retaining member having a retaining end and a cavity engagement surface proximate the retaining end; wherein the latching members each have a latching member aperture extending through a portion of the side wall of the latching member, wherein the retaining member is positioned within the aperture; the retaining member being movable between a compressed position and a non-compressed position, wherein in the non-compressed position the retaining end of the retaining member extends further outward from the aperture than when the retaining member is in its compressed position; and wherein at least one of the latching members is removably coupled to the ring member. 12. The ladder cage of claim 11, further comprising: the latching member having a cavity extending at least partially therein; the cavity ending at an innermost inner wall within the latching member; the latching member aperture extending along a portion of the sidewall proximate the cavity such that the cavity creates a passageway from the exterior of the self-contained latching member to the interior of the cavity; wherein a portion of the retaining member is retained inside the cavity and a portion of the retaining member extends outside of the cavity through the aperture; a resilient member contained within the cavity of the latching member; the resilient member being compressible to allow for compression thereof when pressure is applied to the retainment end of the retainment member, and capable of returning to its original form, or close thereto, when it is no longer in a compressed state; the retaining member having an underside; and wherein a portion of the resilient member is in contact with the underside of the retaining member. 13. The ladder cage of claim 12, further comprising: a plurality of anchor plates spaced along the length of the respective ring members, wherein the anchor plates couple the corresponding latching members to the ring members; 

 each anchor plate having at least one ring attachment member extending therefrom and an aperture extending through a portion of the anchor plate; wherein the at least one ring attachment member attaches the anchor plate to the ring member; the latching member having external threading along a portion of its anchoring end; and wherein the anchoring end is placed within the anchor plate aperture, and an internally threaded fastener is coupled to the external threading of the anchoring end to retain the self- contained latching member in the anchor plate aperture. 14. The ladder cage of claim 13, further comprising: an internal protrusion extending into the latching member cavity opposite the latching member aperture; the resilient member having a base and opposing arms extending from the base; the resilient member base being proximate the innermost inner wall of the cavity; the bottom arm of the resilient member positioned proximate a portion of the internal protrusion; the upper arm of the resilient member being in contact with the underside of the resilient member; a striking plate having at one end the retainment member and at the opposite end a striking end; the latching member having a cavity opening extending through its retaining end; and wherein the striking end at least partially extends out of the cavity at the cavity opening. 15. The ladder cage of claim 14, further comprising: the anchor member having two opposing ring attachment members extending from the anchor member to the ring member and attaching the anchor member to the ring member; the two opposing ring attachment members defining an open space between the anchor member aperture and the ring member; and wherein the internally threaded fastener is disposed within the open space. 16. A method of using latching members, comprising: 

 installing latching members onto a plurality of ring members, wherein the latching members having the ability to couple with and retain the cage ring connecting members thereon without the need for additional external fasteners; and combing adjacent ring members by installing the cage ring connecting members therebetween by utilizing the latching members on the ring members and repeating this step to form a ladder cage. 17. The method of claim 16, wherein the installing latching members step includes removably coupling the latching member to the ring member using a removable fastener. 18. The method of claim 17, further comprising removing a latching member from the ring member through the use of the coupled removable fastener. 19. The method of claim 17, further comprising replacing the previously removed latching member with a new or repaired latching member. 20. The method of claim 19, wherein the replacing step occurs at the work site.
